# Git workflow

## Worktrees (features and fixes)

Use a **worktree** for new features and bugfixes. Do **not** do that work on the main tree (`dev` at repo root). Use the root only for small docs/config, dependency bumps, or when told otherwise.

- **Feature** → e.g. `.worktrees/feat-my-feature` on branch `feat/my-feature`
- **Fix** → e.g. `.worktrees/fix-issue-name` on branch `fix/short-description`

Worktrees live under `.worktrees/` (gitignored). **Folder names use dashes** (not slashes). After `git worktree add`, run setup:

```bash
git worktree add .worktrees/feat-foo dev
bun run worktree:setup feat-foo
bun run worktree:dev feat-foo
```

Use `bun run worktree:list` to inspect worktrees.

## Conventional commits

```
<type>[optional scope]: <description>
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `style`, `refactor`, `perf`, `test`, `chore`. Breaking: `BREAKING CHANGE:` in body/footer, or `feat!:` (etc.).

## Conventional branches

`<type>/<short-description>` — e.g. `feat/user-auth`, `fix/login-loop`. **Do not** use Linear issue IDs as branch names.

## Pull requests

Create with `gh` targeting **`upstream/dev`**. Description: changelog-style (**New Features**, **Bug Fixes**, **Refactors**, **Documentation**, **Tests**).

## Finishing a branch

If the branch changed structure (new dirs, routes, tables, agents, graphs), **update `CLAUDE.md`**. Then merge into `dev`, push **both** remotes (`upstream` and `origin`), delete the branch, remove the worktree (`git worktree remove .worktrees/<name>`).
